        "content": "<p>The <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/List/Destutter.html\">docs</a> for Destutter suggest</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">destutter</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>as an example usage, but Lean 4 complains \"unexpected token '≠'; expected ')', '↑', '↥', '⇑' or term\". I'm guessing this is a Lean 3 vs Lean 4 issue. What's the right syntax, and should those docs be updated?</p>",
        "id": 402964218,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Meiburg",
        "timestamp": 1700372286
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, apparently the new notation is <code>(·≠·)</code>. Well, there's a lot of instances of <code>(+)</code>, <code>(&lt;)</code>, etc. in the comments still in Mathlib :)</p>",
        "id": 402964738,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Meiburg",
        "timestamp": 1700372640
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, this is lean 3 syntax. Do you want to make a pull request?</p>",
        "id": 402968565,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1700374925
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are a lot of instances of this.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Bash\"><pre><span></span><code>&gt;<span class=\"w\"> </span>rg<span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s1\">'\\([+\\-*/=≤&lt;&gt;≥≠⊆]\\)'</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>wc<span class=\"w\"> </span>-l\n<span class=\"m\">154</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
